    slug: "the-virtue-of-tawheed-monotheism",
    description: `The Virtue of Tawheed (Monotheism) is a focused, informative book that explores the central concept of Islamic theology — the oneness of Allah (Tawheed) — and explains its supreme importance in the life of a Muslim. Published by Darussalam, this book systematically presents the different categories of Tawheed as understood in Islamic scholarship: Tawheed ar-Rububiyyah (the oneness of Allah's lordship), Tawheed al-Uluhiyyah (the oneness of worship), and Tawheed al-Asma was-Sifat (the oneness of Allah's names and attributes). Each category is explained with clarity, supported by Quranic evidence and Hadith narrations, and illustrated with practical examples that help readers understand how Tawheed applies to their daily lives.

The book emphasises that Tawheed is not merely an abstract theological concept but the foundation upon which all acts of worship, morality, and social conduct are built. It discusses the virtues and rewards associated with upholding pure Tawheed, including the forgiveness of sins, entry into Paradise, and the pleasure of Allah. Conversely, the book warns against the dangers of shirk (associating partners with Allah) — the one sin that Allah has declared unforgivable if maintained until death — and explains the various forms shirk can take, both obvious and subtle. Topics addressed include the prohibition of grave worship, seeking intercession from other than Allah, wearing amulets and talismans for protection, and attributing divine qualities to created beings.

The text draws from the works of classical scholars including Ibn Taymiyyah, Ibn al-Qayyim, and Muhammad ibn Abdul Wahhab, presenting their arguments in a clear, contemporary English format. The book includes relevant Quranic verses with explanations, Hadith narrations with their sources, and practical guidance on how to safeguard one's Tawheed in an age of diverse influences and deviant beliefs. It is an essential read for Muslims of all levels of knowledge — those new to the faith will gain a clear understanding of Islam's most fundamental principle, while more advanced readers will benefit from the scholarly depth and evidentiary approach. The book is suitable for individual study, group discussion in halaqahs (study circles), and as a supplementary text for courses on Aqeedah (Islamic creed) in Islamic schools and universities.`,
